22:52.040 --> 22:53.200
to know how people are feeling

22:53.200 --> 22:54.920
and to make things that speak to that

22:54.920 --> 22:57.800
that also line up with what I personally believe,

22:57.800 --> 23:00.880
I can sense that undercurrent as can so many other people

23:00.880 --> 23:03.040
and the contrast between it

23:03.040 --> 23:06.640
and the electoral success is like somewhat fascinating.

23:06.640 --> 23:08.240
You see all these positive signs,

23:08.240 --> 23:10.440
but you also see, well, hold on a second,

23:10.440 --> 23:13.040
why aren't politicians who espouse

23:13.040 --> 23:14.840
some of these policies doing better?

23:14.840 --> 23:17.480
But before we get deeper into that, I'd love actually,

23:17.480 --> 23:18.760
I think we waited a little too long

23:18.760 --> 23:20.640
in the podcast to do this.

23:20.640 --> 23:23.480
When you talk about socialism and democratic socialism,

23:23.480 --> 23:25.640
do you have a capsule summary of what you mean by that?

23:25.640 --> 23:27.680
Because I don't want to, you know,

23:27.680 --> 23:28.880
people are maybe feeling in the blank

23:28.880 --> 23:33.040
of what they believe that your political beliefs

23:33.040 --> 23:34.800
or project is.

23:34.800 --> 23:37.200
Well, fundamentally to me, socialism is about

23:37.200 --> 23:40.120
at a minimum securing people's social

23:40.120 --> 23:44.280
and economic necessities and saying that people

23:44.280 --> 23:47.040
are entitled to certain things just by virtue of being born.

23:47.040 --> 23:50.600
So at the very least, that means the state

23:50.600 --> 23:55.600
as a provider of last resort for things like healthcare,

23:56.480 --> 23:59.480
childcare, housing, you know, nutrition.

23:59.480 --> 24:01.880
So they're making sure we have that baseline

24:01.880 --> 24:04.120
of a welfare state.

24:05.040 --> 24:08.000
Secondly, to me, it's about extended democracy

24:08.000 --> 24:11.160
from purely the formal political realm

24:11.160 --> 24:13.920
into the economic realm as well.

24:13.920 --> 24:18.280
So if we were to agree that democracy is a good thing

24:18.280 --> 24:21.640
at the ballot box, why shouldn't we have greater degrees

24:21.640 --> 24:23.600
of democracy at our workplace?

24:23.600 --> 24:27.800
And within those two broad sets of principles,

24:27.800 --> 24:30.040
I think you could have a lot of different forms.

24:30.040 --> 24:35.040
So I don't suppose that a centrally planned economy

24:35.040 --> 24:37.720
would be a great system to live under.

24:37.720 --> 24:40.080
You know, I think there's certain both incentive

24:40.080 --> 24:45.080
and informational problems that arise in those systems.

24:45.680 --> 24:46.760
Yeah.

24:46.760 --> 24:49.080
But you could still have markets

24:49.080 --> 24:52.160
where you have an employee owned

24:52.160 --> 24:55.360
or worker owners controlling their workplaces

24:55.360 --> 24:58.240
and competing with each other to produce goods and services

24:58.240 --> 25:02.960
and a private sector for consumer goods and services

25:02.960 --> 25:05.680
while also having a larger state sector

25:05.680 --> 25:08.320
that secures things like healthcare

25:08.320 --> 25:12.040
or some of the big, what economists would call

25:12.040 --> 25:15.440
natural monopolies like our, you know,

25:15.440 --> 25:17.200
railroad network or things like that

25:17.200 --> 25:20.280
where we feel like maybe it would be fine for there

25:20.280 --> 25:23.720
to just be one actor in the sphere.

25:23.720 --> 25:27.920
And we'd rather not be a giant corporate actor.

25:27.920 --> 25:30.720
We'd rather have the state where in theory

25:30.720 --> 25:34.040
we have greater scope to control the realm of state action.

25:34.040 --> 25:36.800
So as a democratic socialist, part of what I believe in

25:36.800 --> 25:41.800
is in a sense a reconciliation of liberalism and socialism.

25:43.440 --> 25:46.640
So for example, I think rights are great.

25:46.640 --> 25:50.360
And it's great to have this idea that yes, democracy

25:50.360 --> 25:52.520
is excellent in most spheres of life,

25:52.520 --> 25:54.960
but there are certain things where I don't want my neighbor

25:54.960 --> 25:57.840
intruding on my personal consumption choice.

25:57.840 --> 26:01.680
I don't want my neighbor or the majority restricting

26:01.680 --> 26:06.160
on my ability to speak freely or to do my own thing.

26:06.160 --> 26:09.120
And I think those are great aspects of liberalism.

26:09.120 --> 26:12.320
And I think they're perfectly reconcilable

26:12.320 --> 26:16.440
with a socialism that tries to secure people's rights

26:16.440 --> 26:21.440
to develop into individuals that can truly,

26:22.560 --> 26:23.920
you know, reach their potentials

26:23.920 --> 26:28.920
and can participate in this, in our society.

26:29.360 --> 26:32.440
Because, you know, right now I think we take for granted

26:32.440 --> 26:35.360
as Americans that a kid born in, you know,

26:35.360 --> 26:39.640
Fairfield, Connecticut is going to have a radically different

26:41.120 --> 26:44.800
life and life outcomes and opportunities as a kid born,

26:44.800 --> 26:48.920
you know, 20, 30 miles away and in Hartford or Waterbury.

26:48.920 --> 26:51.120
And I'm doing very Connecticut example.

26:51.120 --> 26:56.600
Oh, everybody is aware of the socioeconomic strata

26:56.600 --> 26:58.920
of different Connecticut cities and towns.

26:58.920 --> 27:00.440
I think we all know this.

27:00.440 --> 27:01.280
No, I know what you're talking about.

27:01.280 --> 27:03.080
You're talking about like where I grew up on Long Island

27:03.080 --> 27:04.400
versus Brownsville, Brooklyn, right?

27:04.400 --> 27:07.280
Or pick your neighborhood where you're like,

27:07.280 --> 27:08.840
oh, yeah, that's the bad part of town.

27:08.840 --> 27:10.440
And this is the good part of town, right?

27:10.440 --> 27:13.080
We just take for granted that, you know,

27:13.080 --> 27:16.520
some kids going to public schools in some neighborhoods,

27:16.520 --> 27:18.880
we're not even like Britain where, yeah, of course,

27:18.880 --> 27:21.280
we ship people out to fancy boarding schools

27:21.280 --> 27:22.400
are going to have different outcomes.

27:22.400 --> 27:24.680
But public schools, we take for granted

27:24.680 --> 27:26.640
that some of them are going to produce doctors

27:26.640 --> 27:29.680
and lawyers and engineers and other schools

27:29.680 --> 27:31.640
are going to produce dropouts.

27:31.640 --> 27:35.000
And that's not normal for a rich country

27:35.000 --> 27:37.200
where we could easily solve that problem, not even

27:37.200 --> 27:41.480
through socialist revolution, but through tax and transfers

27:41.480 --> 27:43.640
and investments and jobs programs

27:43.640 --> 27:45.200
and a host of other things.

27:45.200 --> 27:47.160
Yeah, I thought your answer was interesting there

27:47.160 --> 27:51.440
because you sort of gave us the entire scope all the way

27:51.440 --> 27:53.600
from the minimal to the maximal version of socialism.

27:53.600 --> 27:58.080
You ended by talking about a substantially different economic

27:58.080 --> 28:01.040
system that has a lot more state action,

28:01.040 --> 28:03.680
worker cooperatives that are competing with each other.

28:03.680 --> 28:05.520
We could dive into that.

28:05.520 --> 28:08.320
But you also had, on the other hand,

28:08.320 --> 28:13.320
talking about simply expanded social welfare programs

28:13.320 --> 28:14.960
of the kind that we're already used to.

28:14.960 --> 28:17.560
Like we already provide in America

28:17.560 --> 28:20.400
many of the types of programs that you're talking about.

28:20.400 --> 28:24.720
We have a somewhat socialized version of education.

28:24.720 --> 28:27.320
We have public school K through 12.

28:27.320 --> 28:30.280
We do not have that for higher education.

28:30.280 --> 28:32.440
And we could talk about ways that we

28:32.440 --> 28:35.960
could expand that for public education

28:35.960 --> 28:39.000
so that your zip code does not determine how much,

28:39.000 --> 28:41.920
that we don't fund public schools via property taxes,

28:41.920 --> 28:45.480
meaning wealthier areas have better schools.

28:45.480 --> 28:48.200
And what I find really interesting

28:48.200 --> 28:50.480
is that in the last couple of years,

28:50.480 --> 28:55.520
we have tested a lot of the most immediate socialist ideas

28:55.520 --> 28:56.800
if we want to label them that way.

28:56.800 --> 29:02.640
During the pandemic, there was massively increased welfare

29:02.640 --> 29:05.480
payment or welfare payments of general kinds

29:05.480 --> 29:07.200
to folks during the pandemic.

29:07.200 --> 29:13.480
We had expanded tax credits, child welfare, et cetera,

29:13.480 --> 29:15.520
unemployment benefits.

29:15.520 --> 29:19.960
And those had huge beneficial impacts on people's lives

29:19.960 --> 29:22.200
that then a couple of years later were removed.

29:22.200 --> 29:24.560
Also, going back to the 2020 election,

29:24.600 --> 29:26.720
when Joe Biden came into office,

29:26.720 --> 29:33.040
he at least acted as though he was going to be much more of a,

29:33.040 --> 29:34.240
I don't want to say a socialist,

29:34.240 --> 29:37.360
but he was proclaiming himself sort

29:37.360 --> 29:39.080
of the next coming of FDR, right?

29:39.080 --> 29:40.920
He was going to do New Deal-style stuff.

29:40.920 --> 29:43.560
And he did some of it, giant infrastructure spending,

29:43.560 --> 29:45.600
et cetera, antitrust enforcement.

29:45.600 --> 29:48.080
Those were all things that I expected an Elizabeth Warren

29:48.080 --> 29:51.880
or a Bernie Sanders president to do, not a Joe Biden.

29:51.880 --> 29:57.000
And so it feels on the policy level, holy shit,

29:57.000 --> 30:00.320
some of these things have become not impossible in America,

30:00.320 --> 30:02.560
even if we're not sure if they're going to stick around.

30:02.560 --> 30:03.720
Do you have any view on that?

30:03.720 --> 30:06.400
Yeah, I think that one interesting, first of all,

30:06.400 --> 30:08.840
I think that the infrastructure bill

30:08.840 --> 30:11.800
was a positive development.

30:11.800 --> 30:13.640
It was over a trillion dollars of funding

30:13.640 --> 30:16.920
for Roadsbridge's mass transit rail service.

30:16.920 --> 30:18.320
Obviously, that's better than what

30:18.320 --> 30:20.520
we would have gotten from a Trump administration.

30:20.520 --> 30:26.320
Obviously, it's a policy success.

30:26.320 --> 30:31.640
But I guess that sometimes the United States,

30:31.640 --> 30:35.720
the reason why a lot of Americans feel like, oh, well,

30:35.720 --> 30:39.320
we're already trying massive socialist-style spending

30:39.320 --> 30:42.800
in the US, and we already have this massive welfare state,

30:42.800 --> 30:46.760
but it just doesn't work, is because we tend

30:46.760 --> 30:49.680
to have quite inefficiently designed programs.

30:50.680 --> 30:53.040
When we do spend money on welfare,

30:53.040 --> 30:57.160
we needlessly mean-tested, and we waste time and resources,

30:57.160 --> 30:59.320
and we weaken these programs by saying,

