44:56.240 --> 44:58.880
because the members think,

44:58.880 --> 45:01.160
well, hold on a second, I have great healthcare now,

45:01.160 --> 45:02.720
I don't know what this plan would be like,

45:02.720 --> 45:03.680
maybe it would be worse.

45:03.680 --> 45:06.440
A, there's a huge education hurdle,

45:06.440 --> 45:08.520
but then also sometimes the leadership of the unions

45:08.560 --> 45:11.160
is like, well, healthcare is what we provide.

45:11.160 --> 45:14.080
Like that is why people are excited to be a member

45:14.080 --> 45:16.920
of the union is because they get the healthcare.

45:16.920 --> 45:18.760
So if we don't give healthcare,

45:18.760 --> 45:21.480
how do we know that we can get our members to show up

45:21.480 --> 45:22.720
if we need to go on strike, et cetera?

45:22.720 --> 45:24.560
Maybe they won't need us as much anymore.

45:24.560 --> 45:26.360
And so those are, and by the way,

45:26.360 --> 45:30.440
those are ways that good people in good faith

45:30.440 --> 45:32.000
in the movement can end up,

45:32.000 --> 45:34.680
the incentives push them in that direction.

45:34.680 --> 45:38.480
And so it seems like there's still,

45:38.480 --> 45:41.440
even though it all pencils outright,

45:41.440 --> 45:44.200
there are sort of institutional barriers,

45:44.200 --> 45:47.720
even in folks who, you would think that as a socialist,

45:47.720 --> 45:50.920
you would be in the movement with,

45:50.920 --> 45:52.520
with folks in the labor movement.

45:52.520 --> 45:55.320
It's like an internal tension there.

45:55.320 --> 45:56.680
Yeah, definitely, definitely.

45:56.680 --> 45:59.400
I think that there's a lot of unions

45:59.400 --> 46:02.880
who basically don't trust the government

46:02.920 --> 46:05.880
to create a plan as good as what their members enjoy now,

46:05.880 --> 46:08.240
or at least they feel like the union members

46:08.240 --> 46:09.960
feel that way in the private sector.

46:09.960 --> 46:12.160
And there's also some other unions that are afraid

46:12.160 --> 46:15.440
that if there's a continued push

46:15.440 --> 46:18.880
to make union membership volunteer,

46:18.880 --> 46:21.400
so kind of open shops instead of closed shops,

46:21.400 --> 46:26.240
that having kind of access to health insurance

46:26.240 --> 46:29.040
and people get accessing those plans

46:29.040 --> 46:30.720
through their union membership

46:30.720 --> 46:33.160
is a potentially really important part

46:33.160 --> 46:35.000
of keeping people in unions.

46:35.000 --> 46:37.840
But I think these are ultimately pretty short-sighted.

46:37.840 --> 46:40.680
I also think it's short-sighted for US industry

46:40.680 --> 46:44.640
as a whole, particularly, let's say the US auto industry

46:44.640 --> 46:49.320
that's competing with, historically competing with

46:49.320 --> 46:53.280
labor in Japan and in Germany,

46:53.280 --> 46:56.320
places that the state plays a much bigger role

46:56.320 --> 47:00.560
in health provision, but are, you know,

47:00.560 --> 47:03.000
kind of at a competitive disadvantage.

47:03.000 --> 47:06.000
I think the counter is that employers

47:07.040 --> 47:10.320
like having this major benefit

47:10.320 --> 47:12.920
that everybody needs tied to employment

47:12.920 --> 47:15.440
because it keeps people at their firms.

47:15.440 --> 47:18.280
And again, they make the calculation

47:18.280 --> 47:23.280
that it may be the control that they get over workers

47:23.320 --> 47:27.320
and this leverage is more important than the savings.

47:27.320 --> 47:29.800
But I think there's a host of small businesses

47:29.800 --> 47:34.800
and others that would benefit from not having this burden.

47:36.960 --> 47:39.280
Yeah, I mean, I think you're right that it's short-sighted.

47:39.280 --> 47:42.280
It's a sort of short-term or current benefit

47:42.280 --> 47:44.520
that some of these actors currently enjoy,

47:44.520 --> 47:48.520
but that is preventing them from a greater long-term benefit.

47:48.520 --> 47:50.360
And yeah, I'm just curious from your view,

47:50.360 --> 47:51.960
how do we make progress on it?

47:52.000 --> 47:55.320
You said, you know, it sort of needs a leader

47:55.320 --> 47:57.960
like Bernie spreading the message,

47:57.960 --> 47:59.600
but Bernie did the best job of it,

47:59.600 --> 48:01.200
anyone's done in 30 years.

48:01.200 --> 48:04.160
And, you know, again, you know, the wave rolled in,

48:04.160 --> 48:06.840
but then went back.

48:06.840 --> 48:10.520
And so are there, you know, in terms of this,

48:10.520 --> 48:12.280
just looking at socialized medicine,

48:12.280 --> 48:15.520
how does one build progress towards that

48:15.520 --> 48:16.760
over the next few decades?

48:16.760 --> 48:18.520
So the reason why I keep mentioning Bernie

48:18.520 --> 48:20.560
as someone who's obviously my politics

48:20.680 --> 48:24.840
are probably a step or two to Bernie's left in certain ways.

48:24.840 --> 48:27.680
And I was a member of Socialist Movement

48:27.680 --> 48:32.000
way before the first Bernie campaign in 2015, 2016.

48:33.000 --> 48:35.480
But I keep mentioning him because I think

48:35.480 --> 48:38.080
that we're in such a hollowed-out political environment

48:39.560 --> 48:43.720
that we actually need big national politics

48:43.720 --> 48:45.760
and politics at the level of communications

48:45.760 --> 48:47.400
and politics at the level of almost like

48:47.400 --> 48:50.120
a national kind of populist articulation,

48:50.120 --> 48:52.120
the way that Trump provides it on the right.

48:52.120 --> 48:55.120
And I think Bernie for a time was providing on the left

48:55.120 --> 48:59.080
to break through this hollowed-out environment,

48:59.080 --> 49:02.440
to break through and to re-engage people with politics.

49:02.440 --> 49:04.920
So in the 2016 campaign,

49:04.920 --> 49:09.000
you saw for the first time Trump and Bernie both

49:09.000 --> 49:11.480
rallying people by the tens of thousands.

49:11.480 --> 49:13.600
Yeah, it was displays that,

49:13.600 --> 49:17.080
obviously there was a little bit of this in Obama's 2008 run,

49:17.120 --> 49:19.960
but it's something that reminds you of politics

49:19.960 --> 49:22.000
in another country, not politics,

49:22.000 --> 49:26.240
as we've known it growing up in the United States.

49:26.240 --> 49:30.840
Yeah, arena rallies for political candidates.

49:30.840 --> 49:33.640
That's not something that people were doing for Al Gore.

49:33.640 --> 49:36.560
Definitely, it would be like a once a year,

49:36.560 --> 49:39.040
they'll just do it at the DNC.

49:39.040 --> 49:40.280
You remember he did the weird thing

49:40.280 --> 49:44.000
where he kind of rebuffed Bill Clinton a little bit

49:44.000 --> 49:48.120
and aggressively made out with his wife, Al Gore.

49:48.120 --> 49:49.120
I don't remember that,

49:49.120 --> 49:50.960
but I'm gonna look it up after this show.

49:50.960 --> 49:54.440
It was kind of a like, I'm Al Gore and I live my wife.

49:54.440 --> 49:57.840
You know, that guy doesn't love his wife.

49:57.840 --> 49:59.080
I'm a wife guy.

49:59.080 --> 50:01.360
Yeah, yeah, exactly, exactly.

50:01.360 --> 50:04.280
So, you know, I think that in this environment

50:04.280 --> 50:05.160
that's so hollowed out,

50:05.160 --> 50:07.360
one, it means that even a group as small

50:07.360 --> 50:10.840
as Democratic Socialist America or other small groups

50:10.840 --> 50:13.480
like Justice Democrats or Sunrise

50:13.480 --> 50:16.360
can actually make a difference because,

50:16.360 --> 50:18.160
and on the other side,

50:18.160 --> 50:21.280
obviously the anti-abortion activists

50:21.280 --> 50:22.120
and the Christian right

50:22.120 --> 50:23.920
can kind of make a huge difference too.

50:23.920 --> 50:28.000
With a small group of highly motivated organizers

50:28.000 --> 50:29.560
in a hollowed out political environment

50:29.560 --> 50:31.560
can have disproportionate influence.

50:31.560 --> 50:35.000
But I think that the goal of campaigns

50:35.000 --> 50:37.040
like the Sanders campaign has to be

50:37.040 --> 50:39.960
to spur people out of this malaise,

50:39.960 --> 50:42.160
then get them motivated and activated

50:42.160 --> 50:44.600
and give them a language that they could use,

50:44.600 --> 50:45.680
a framework that they could use,

50:45.680 --> 50:48.040
a set of demands that they can identify with.

50:48.040 --> 50:53.040
Where Bernie failed was that he wasn't successfully able

50:53.120 --> 50:57.760
to carry on his campaign even in a limited form

50:57.760 --> 50:59.240
through some permanent organ.

50:59.240 --> 51:02.400
So in other words, he tried to do our revolution

51:02.400 --> 51:03.440
which kind of went nowhere

51:03.440 --> 51:06.000
and he tried to do these other efforts

51:06.000 --> 51:07.480
to make his campaign permanent.

51:07.480 --> 51:09.760
But that's not something he was particularly good at.

51:09.760 --> 51:12.280
So it was up to us on the far left

51:12.280 --> 51:15.920
to build organizations like the Democratic Social for America.

51:15.920 --> 51:19.360
Whereas I think that socials politics in America

51:19.360 --> 51:21.520
is obviously what I believe in, I think it's important.

51:21.520 --> 51:23.960
But I think there's probably a broader base

51:23.960 --> 51:28.440
of for egalitarian, pro-working class politics in America

51:28.440 --> 51:33.080
that uses probably is more ideologically diffuse

51:33.080 --> 51:36.780
and also uses a different sort of language

51:36.780 --> 51:39.600
than the socials left does in the United States.

51:39.600 --> 51:43.160
But that fundamentally stands for a fairer deal

51:43.160 --> 51:46.840
for working class people and stands for defense

51:46.840 --> 51:51.480
and expansion of important social programs

51:51.480 --> 51:53.440
like Medicare for all.

51:53.440 --> 51:55.800
When you say a different sort of language

51:55.800 --> 51:57.080
than the socialists left,

51:57.080 --> 51:59.080
what do you mean than the current socialists left?

51:59.080 --> 52:01.880
Well, I think the socialists left right now,

52:01.880 --> 52:06.720
we are activists but without a huge social base.

52:06.720 --> 52:09.360
So a lot of us come from working class backgrounds

52:09.360 --> 52:12.560
and a lot of us are involved in campaigns

52:12.560 --> 52:15.000
that do connect with a lot of working class people.

52:15.000 --> 52:18.380
Like for example, there's a lot of DSA members

52:18.380 --> 52:20.920
who are actively involved in tenant rights struggles

52:20.920 --> 52:24.360
that do have an important base.

52:24.360 --> 52:29.360
But fundamentally we join DSA in ones and twos.

52:29.800 --> 52:33.960
So we often create a hot house

52:33.960 --> 52:38.700
where certain language and ideological distinctions

52:38.700 --> 52:41.620
that are not really that important or consequential

52:41.620 --> 52:45.660
to people's lives day to day take on greater consequence.

52:45.660 --> 52:47.140
Right.

52:47.140 --> 52:48.740
A lot of people reading books

52:48.740 --> 52:51.500
and getting very heated about them in closed door meetings

52:51.500 --> 52:52.820
is what you're talking about.

52:52.820 --> 52:56.380
Yeah, I wish the meetings were closed doors.

52:56.380 --> 53:00.140
So sometimes they go viral, yeah.

53:00.140 --> 53:02.780
The interesting arguments, yeah.

53:04.260 --> 53:07.180
And again, I think building a base of cadre

53:07.180 --> 53:12.180
to think about some of these more theoretical points

53:12.500 --> 53:15.380
or are committed or keep alive some of this whole language.

53:15.380 --> 53:18.100
I actually think it's useful in certain ways.

53:18.100 --> 53:22.060
But if you're not connected to a real social base,

53:22.060 --> 53:26.020
you're not challenged to try to articulate your ideas

53:26.020 --> 53:28.140
in a way every single day,

53:28.140 --> 53:32.940
in a way that wins over ordinary Americans

53:32.940 --> 53:35.420
and all their complexities.

53:35.860 --> 53:37.820
So I think that's the...

53:40.740 --> 53:44.900
Yang to Trump to back to Yang to now RFK,

53:46.260 --> 53:48.580
junior curious teamster.

53:48.580 --> 53:50.460
Like literally someone I spoke to yesterday.

53:50.460 --> 53:51.300
So...

53:51.300 --> 53:52.140
Right.

53:53.140 --> 53:55.180
And who's a person of color, by the way, which makes it...

53:55.180 --> 53:56.020
Yeah.

53:56.020 --> 53:57.420
I think that's a lot of this election

53:57.420 --> 54:03.420
because even a lot of our priors about Hispanic voters

54:03.620 --> 54:06.900
vis-a-vis Trump is not gonna be true in this election either.

54:06.900 --> 54:08.820
And the RFK junior factor is something

54:08.820 --> 54:11.060
that I personally just have not considered much

54:11.060 --> 54:12.100
until recently.

54:12.100 --> 54:13.940
Now it just seems like he's not gonna go away

54:13.940 --> 54:16.340
and he's gonna get his 15%

54:16.340 --> 54:19.540
and maybe I'm just hoping only eight of those 15

54:19.540 --> 54:22.020
will be from Biden and the rest will be from Trump.

54:22.020 --> 54:23.540
You think he's gonna get 15,

54:23.540 --> 54:26.740
you think RFK is gonna get 15% of the popular vote?

54:26.740 --> 54:29.820
I think that, well, a lot of, I think,

54:29.820 --> 54:31.580
polling would have him close to that.

54:31.580 --> 54:34.420
I think in reality, as we closer to the election,

54:34.420 --> 54:36.300
it'll become more and more polarized.

54:36.300 --> 54:41.300
I think that that RFK vote will dissipate back

54:41.380 --> 54:45.060
to both Trumps, probably 55% of it might go to Biden,

54:45.060 --> 54:46.940
the rest will go to Trump.

54:46.940 --> 54:51.540
And I think that the best bet,

54:51.540 --> 54:52.780
I'm one of the few people,

54:52.780 --> 54:54.740
and I feel like the few people in the world

54:54.740 --> 54:56.420
that just thinks that Biden's gonna win,

54:56.420 --> 55:00.260
if only because I feel like he's been hit so hard

55:00.300 --> 55:02.460
with all these negatives for so many months

55:02.460 --> 55:04.980
that it's only gonna go up from here.

55:04.980 --> 55:07.780
And Trump between his legal trouble

55:07.780 --> 55:11.380
and between just the sheer amount of vitriol

55:11.380 --> 55:13.620
that a portion of Americans have for him,

55:13.620 --> 55:17.460
I just feel like the negative polarization

55:17.460 --> 55:21.420
is people like to call it of the race.

55:21.420 --> 55:24.020
Well, we'll skew in Biden's favor

55:24.020 --> 55:25.820
because we already lived through Trump

55:25.820 --> 55:28.180
and we have, I think, concerns

55:28.180 --> 55:32.860
that the next four years of Trump would be even worse.

55:32.860 --> 55:36.060
And I just feel like that's the thing

55:36.060 --> 55:39.140
that'll motivate people who are quite discontent

55:39.140 --> 55:41.900
with Biden, like myself, to vote for him.

55:41.900 --> 55:44.660
And I would vote for Biden if I was in a swing state.

55:44.660 --> 55:48.380
I'm in New York, so I'll vote for Jill Stein or something.

55:49.940 --> 55:51.580
You know why I vote for Jill Stein?

55:51.580 --> 55:53.020
Because Jill Stein asked me,

55:53.020 --> 55:55.780
hey, Basker, are you gonna vote for me in 2016?

55:55.780 --> 55:56.780
I'm like, when?

55:56.780 --> 55:58.260
No one else hit me up.

55:58.260 --> 55:59.820
I'm not sure if it's an effective way

55:59.820 --> 56:02.660
to win a national campaign.

56:03.820 --> 56:05.700
She personally asked you.

56:05.700 --> 56:06.620
Yeah, yeah.

56:06.620 --> 56:09.820
Well, okay, but some people will say,

56:09.820 --> 56:11.820
and let's go back.

56:11.820 --> 56:13.460
Oh, actually, before I get to that,

56:13.460 --> 56:15.860
I do wanna make one point that you were talking about

56:15.860 --> 56:20.660
somebody who speaks to an actual group of working people

56:20.660 --> 56:22.300
that reminds you of, say, Sean Fain,

56:22.300 --> 56:24.700
who is saying a lot of those ideas,

56:24.700 --> 56:27.420
why do we even have billionaires, et cetera,

56:27.420 --> 56:29.340
things that maybe Bernie could have said,

56:29.340 --> 56:31.380
or that a DSA leader would say,

56:31.380 --> 56:34.420
but he's saying them to his actual members,

56:34.420 --> 56:37.780
who he understands, he knows them well,

56:37.780 --> 56:39.700
and he's trying to get them to go on strike

56:39.700 --> 56:42.820
or sign a union card or whatever it is,

56:42.820 --> 56:45.940
and that's really rooted to their struggle.

56:45.940 --> 56:50.940
It's not someone like myself at a DSA meeting

56:51.260 --> 56:52.580
with a college education saying,

56:52.580 --> 56:53.780
hey, here's what I think would be good

56:53.780 --> 56:56.660
for some people who I haven't met, for example,

56:56.660 --> 57:00.340
and that's a real difference that is meaningful, perhaps.

57:01.660 --> 57:03.820
Going back to the national election, though,

57:03.820 --> 57:08.820
you, there were people who said the same thing

57:09.460 --> 57:11.060
that you just said, I'll vote for Jill Stein

57:11.060 --> 57:14.020
because I'm pretty sure that Biden's gonna win.

57:14.020 --> 57:15.980
You did say you'd vote for him if you lived in a swing state,

57:15.980 --> 57:18.460
but there are people who said similar things in 2016,

57:18.460 --> 57:19.780
and other people are very mad at them

57:19.780 --> 57:21.940
because everyone thought Hillary Clinton was gonna win,

57:22.060 --> 57:23.980
and hey, I can just, you know,

57:23.980 --> 57:26.940
I can do whatever I want, right, for that reason.

57:27.860 --> 57:31.380
And I think this year,

57:31.380 --> 57:34.380
something that is really going to give Biden

57:34.380 --> 57:38.020
a lot of trouble is what's happening in Gaza right now,

57:38.020 --> 57:40.540
the support for Israel, et cetera,

57:40.540 --> 57:42.860
and it strikes me that this has been

57:42.860 --> 57:46.220
such a wedge through the entire left.

57:46.220 --> 57:50.340
The, you know, you had DSA members writing an open letter

57:50.340 --> 57:51.900
about why they're leaving DSA,

57:51.900 --> 57:54.260
because of, da-da-da-da-da-da, go down, you know,

57:54.260 --> 57:56.380
they wrote their DSA national leadership,

57:56.380 --> 58:00.780
put out a message that was, et cetera, et cetera, et cetera.

58:00.780 --> 58:03.260
You've had this happen at, you know,

58:03.260 --> 58:06.980
leftist groups and meetings throughout the country

58:06.980 --> 58:09.420
in local democratic parties, et cetera.

58:10.860 --> 58:12.780
And, you know, I've heard a lot of people say,

58:12.780 --> 58:16.220
hey, this is, regardless of how you feel about that,

58:16.220 --> 58:18.060
we are talking about, you know,

58:18.060 --> 58:20.320
we're talking about America's economic needs, right,

58:20.320 --> 58:21.960
and building socialism in America.

58:21.960 --> 58:25.080
This is a, you know, maybe this is not a distraction

58:25.080 --> 58:27.000
because we are a part of what's happening in Israel,

58:27.000 --> 58:31.120
but it's a very, you know, it's such a wrench

58:31.120 --> 58:33.640
to be thrown in at such a vulnerable moment.

58:34.560 --> 58:37.200
And so I'm curious to get into that piece of it.

58:37.200 --> 58:40.720
How do you think that the, you know,

58:40.720 --> 58:44.040
Israel's offensive against the civilians in Gaza

58:44.040 --> 58:47.200
has affected your movement?

58:48.200 --> 58:50.800
Well, I think among DSA, if anything,

58:51.840 --> 58:56.560
having the focal point of solidarity work with Palestine

58:56.560 --> 59:01.560
has been a uniting factor in the organization as a whole.

59:01.640 --> 59:03.600
I think there's some older members who objected

59:03.600 --> 59:06.920
to some of the rhetoric used right after

59:06.920 --> 59:09.040
the October 7th attacks.

59:09.040 --> 59:11.640
And I think their argument was basically,

59:11.640 --> 59:16.640
you're using a rhetoric that is preemptively condemning

59:17.880 --> 59:22.880
Israel for the response rather than focusing on

59:23.080 --> 59:26.840
the actual attack in which hundreds of civilians died,

59:26.840 --> 59:29.000
and also using rhetoric in some cases

59:29.000 --> 59:30.880
that maybe it was more appropriate

59:30.880 --> 59:34.720
to national liberation movements in the 60s and 70s

59:34.720 --> 59:39.560
than it is to an Islamist group like Hamas.

59:39.560 --> 59:44.560
I think that obviously I try to aim for some of the,

59:45.440 --> 59:48.680
in general, try to aim for a broad-based rhetoric

59:48.680 --> 59:51.040
that tries to speak beyond the converted.

59:51.040 --> 59:53.160
So I think there's probably some truth in that

59:53.160 --> 59:54.600
and some of the initial communications.

59:54.600 --> 59:57.320
But as a whole, I think in a moral and ethical sense,

59:57.320 --> 01:00:00.120
I think DSA kind of got it right,

01:00:00.120 --> 01:00:04.360
which is that there was definitely going to be

01:00:04.360 --> 01:00:07.600
a huge and disproportionate Israeli response

01:00:07.600 --> 01:00:11.040
on a largely civilian population.

01:00:11.040 --> 01:00:16.040
And I think a lot of the Democratic Party,

01:00:16.600 --> 01:00:18.960
particularly younger Democrats,

01:00:18.960 --> 01:00:22.560
much less the far left, are united in thinking

01:00:22.560 --> 01:00:24.760
that Israel's actions have been disproportionate,

01:00:24.760 --> 01:00:26.040
that it's targeted civilians,

01:00:26.040 --> 01:00:28.960
and that there needs to be an immediate ceasefire.

01:00:28.960 --> 01:00:31.000
I think they were even hearing those sorts of things

01:00:31.000 --> 01:00:33.760
in tepid ways from the Biden administration itself

01:00:33.760 --> 01:00:36.600
or firm figures within the State Department,

01:00:36.600 --> 01:00:41.600
which shows a pretty wide spectrum of belief.

01:00:45.760 --> 01:00:50.280
So I do think that Biden hasn't exhibited

01:00:50.280 --> 01:00:52.560
the courage that he needed to.

01:00:52.560 --> 01:00:55.080
I think he's done just enough

01:00:55.080 --> 01:00:59.240
that history won't say that he was Netanyahu.

